<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Tinting" class="currentChild" href="Tinting">Tinting</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
A general scum that forms on non-image areas of the printing plate and is transferred to the paper. Originally believed to be caused by contaminants from coated paper, it is now known that tinting is more a function of plate <a title="Desensitization" href="Desensitization">desensitization</a>, various ink formulations, <a title="Fountain Solution" href="Fountain_Solution">fountain solution</a> problems, and other aspects of press chemistry, in particular the <a title="Emulsification" href="Emulsification">emulsification</a> of the ink by the fountain solution. In particular, tinting occurs when particles of ink <a title="Pigment" href="Pigment">pigment</a> bleed into the fountain solution, and are transferred to the non-image areas of the plate, printing as a colored tint. The tendency for tinting to increase with increasing temperature has resulted in its also being known as <a title="Hot-Weather Scumming" href="Hot-Weather_Scumming">hot-weather scumming</a>. Tinting is rarely a problem anymore. Tinting is also known as <a title="washing" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/washing">washing</a>, and in <a title="waterless printing" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/waterless_printing">waterless printing</a> is known as <a title="Toning" href="Toning">toning</a>. 
</p>
